Price Optimisation: Can we find an optimial price for every product of a Cafe, that would maximise profits?¶

Pricing a product is a crucial aspect in any business. Alot of thought process is out into it. There are different strategies to price different kinds of products. There are products whose sales are quite sensitive to their prices and as such a small change in their price can lead to noticeable change in their sales. While there are products whose sales are not much affected by their price - these tend to be either luxury items or necessities (like certain medicines). This notebook will focus on the former type of products.

Price elasticity of demand (Epd), or elasticity, is the degree to which the effective desire for something changes as its price changes. In general, people desire things less as those things become more expensive. However, for some products, the customer's desire could drop sharply even with a little price increase, and for other products, it could stay almost the same even with a big price increase. Economists use the term elasticity to denote this sensitivity to price increases. More precisely, price elasticity gives the percentage change in quantity demanded when there is a one percent increase in price, holding everything else constant.

Mathematically speaking, the price elasticity of demand is defined to be the percentage change in quantity demanded, q,divided by the percentage change in price, p. The formula for the price elasticity (ǫ) is: $$e = \%ΔQ/ \%ΔP$$

In this work, we shall look at the sales of the items of a cafe. Do we see price elasticity for our product? Can we find an optimal price? Will it depend on certain other factors?

Problem Statement: Can we find, for every product, a price that would maximise company daily revenue?¶

What's the plan?¶

1) Do we need to optimise product wise? If, so, which products in order of priority? 2) Are there other factors other than price influencing quantity sold? 3) Can we model quantity sold product wise with good confidence? 4) Are quantity sold for a given product negatively associated with quantity sold for another? 5) How to reach a formula that would maximise company wide revenue?

There may be an optimisation conflict here. Maybe optimising for one product, may cause cannibalisation and decrease sales for another, even at the "optimal price". Should that happen, maybe we should prioritise optimising for the most revenue generating product. Let's keep that in mind for later, in the meantime, let's look at the current cafe performance accross products, and as a whole, and try and identify useful patterns

There seems to be something illogical about the source data, which is that the burger itself costs more than the burger with beverages. Maybe the burger when sold by itself is of a bigger size. Or there are different burgers. Nonetheless, we will keep the data as is.

The Burger is the star product, it brings daily about 2.5 x revenue from the second highest revenue generating product, the burger coke and coffee. Which also generates about 2x revenue from the third highest revenue generating product, the burger and coke.

Not all products sell the same and have similar impact on our cafe's revenue. So we will have to tackle the problem product wise. Our order of priority is: Burger, Burger Coke Coffee, Burger Coke, Burger Lemonade

To better estimate the expectation and variance of our yearly revenue and quantity sold, we will have to also do it per product

  • The Burger daily quantity sold distribution seems to be the combination of two (somewhat) normal distributions, one centered aroud 65 daily Burgers sold, and another one around 90 daily Burgers sold. EDA conclusion¶

  • The Burger is the star product and tends to heavily influence the revenue of the cafe. Optimising for this product in priority should be key
  • Variables which seem interesting to play with, in order to maximise quantity sold, are price, warmer/colder times, and weekday/weekend. The others either show no association, or make little sense to leverage business wise. They could be still analysed later, after a first round of optimisation. Let's consider for now, to start simple and pragmatically, with price, weekend/weekday, and time of the year. Also this would lead to more smooth and stable prices over time, which may be better business wise

Let's know verify above assumptions, hypothesis around whether price and time of the year do have significative association with quantity, with linear regression and statistical hypothesis testing. Let's also find out the scale of these potential association, to get the price elasticity per product, season, and day of the week

    # Scale the predictor variables. Price and dummy variables not on the same scale

    # Add column names back to X_scaled

    y = dataset[y_variable].reset_index(drop=True)
    X_scaled = X_scaled.reset_index(drop=True)

    # Add a constant to X_scaled
    X_scaled = sm.add_constant(X_scaled)

Preliminary conclusions from quantity vs price / season / weekend modelling¶

  • For every products, all features show significant association
  • By order of decreasing magnitude: Weekend/Weekday, Price, Warmer/Colder times
  • From the residuals analysis, we can see that, for all products except the Burger, the residuals look very close to a normal distribution, and this is important for robust interpretability of association between the predictors and quantity sold. We can safely use the coefficients provided by the linear regression as equation for modelling the quantity sold
  • For the burger, we suspect a bit of "Heteroskedasticity" when looking at the residuals vs fitted values, which show a slight cone shape. The residuals QQ plot also show a small deviation against the normal distribution. However, when looking at the residuals distribution, they seem quite well centered around 0, which is good, and the spread seems close to constant. I think we are safe to use the coefficients provided for the burger. Let's also not forget that the daily quantity sold distribution for the burger is not normal but bi normal. That has an impact on above.
  • The VIF analysis also showed no problematic multicollinearity between features
  • we can know perform again a linear regression, on price only, for every product, whether we are in weekend or weekday, or whether in colder times or not, or without taking into consideration any of these features. And get estimated daily revenue, and then yearly revenue from the daily revenue. Let's get, for the Burger, a price for every combination of weekday/weekend and warmer/colder, and for the other products a constant price for now, but should the need be, we can also do like the Burger and get a weekend / weekday price

# Perform linear regression and store the equations
linear_equations = []

dataset_names = ["Colder Weekday Burger", "Colder Weekend Burger", "Warmer Weekday Burger", "Warmer Weekend Burger"]

coefficients = {}  # Dictionary to store coefficients


fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 8))

for i, (dataset_name, dataset) in enumerate(zip(dataset_names, burger_datasets)):
    X = sm.add_constant(dataset["PRICE"])  # Add a constant term to the independent variable
    y = dataset["QUANTITY"]

    model = sm.OLS(y, X)  # Create an ordinary least squares (OLS) model
    results = model.fit()  # Fit the model to the data

    # Store the linear equation
    constant = results.params['const']
    coefficient = results.params['PRICE']
    equation = f"Quantity = {constant:.2f} + {coefficient:.2f} * Price"
    linear_equations.append(equation)
    
    # Store the coefficients and their score in a dictionary
    coefficients[dataset_name] = [constant,coefficient]

    # Calculate RMSE
    y_pred = results.predict(X)
    rmse = np.sqrt(np.mean((y - y_pred) ** 2))

    # Plot actual QUANTITY values against PRICE values
    ax = axes[i // 2, i % 2]
    ax.scatter(dataset["PRICE"], y, label='Actual QUANTITY')
    ax.plot(dataset["PRICE"], results.fittedvalues, color='red', label='Linear Regression')  # Plot the linear regression line
    ax.set_xlabel("PRICE")
    ax.set_ylabel("QUANTITY")
    ax.set_title(dataset_name)
    ax.legend()

    # Add linear equation formula to the plot
    ax.text(0.05, 0.9, equation, transform=ax.transAxes, fontsize=10)

Increasing the quantity sold for a product will not, based on historical data, lead to decreasing the quantity sold for another. That would have been an issue if we wanted to optimise for Burger Coke or Burger Lemonade, our two lowest revenue generating product, and if that had a negative impact of the sales of our two star products, Burger and BCC

We can safely use our above linear equations for every product, and find the price that maximises both quantity and revenue

def find_optimal_price(data, coefficients, buying_price, data_name):
    start_price = data.PRICE.min() - 1              # start price
    end_price = data.PRICE.min() + 10               # end price
    test = pd.DataFrame(columns=["PRICE", "QUANTITY"])  # choose required columns
    test['PRICE'] = np.arange(start_price, end_price, 0.01)
    test['QUANTITY'] = coefficients[0] + coefficients[1] * test["PRICE"]         # make predictions
    test['PROFIT'] = (test["PRICE"] - buying_price) * test["QUANTITY"]
    test['NEW_ADDED_PROFIT'] = test['PROFIT'] - ((data.PRICE.iloc[-1] - buying_price) * test['QUANTITY']) ## Impact on current profits
    test['IMPACT_ON_LATEST_PROFITS'] = 100.0 * test['NEW_ADDED_PROFIT'] / test['PROFIT'] 

    # Plot the results
    plt.plot(test['PRICE'], test['QUANTITY'], label='Quantity')
    plt.plot(test['PRICE'], test['PROFIT'], label='Profit')
    plt.title(data_name)  # Set the title to the name of the data
    plt.xlabel("Price")
    plt.ylabel("Quantity/Profit")
    
    # Find the maximum profit point
    ind = np.argmax(test['PROFIT'])
    max_profit_price = test.loc[ind, 'PRICE']
    max_profit = test.loc[ind, 'PROFIT']
    new_added_profits = test.loc[ind, 'NEW_ADDED_PROFIT']
    impact_on_current_profits = test.loc[ind, 'IMPACT_ON_LATEST_PROFITS']
    
    # Plot the point with maximum profit
    plt.scatter(max_profit_price, max_profit, color='red', label='Max Profit')
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    values_at_max_profit = test.iloc[ind]
    return values_at_max_profit
